## Step 1 — Create Runner Token

Since admin UI access to `gitlab.ttmtech.com` is not available, the runner token is created via the GitLab Rails console on the server. This is the standard GitLab method for creating instance runners from the command line.

```bash
ssh root@aamhilgitlab01

gitlab-rails runner "
runner = Ci::Runner.new(
  runner_type: :instance_type,
  description: 'hillsborough-k8s-runner',
  run_untagged: true,
  active: true
)
runner.save!
puts 'Token: ' + runner.token
"
```

> **Note:** Save the token — it is used in the Helm values below.

This creates a brand new instance runner without modifying any existing runners or settings.

-----

## Step 2 — TLS Certificate

`gitlab.ttmtech.com` uses a DigiCert wildcard certificate. The runner needs to trust the DigiCert CA chain to communicate with GitLab securely.

```bash
# Download DigiCert intermediate CA
curl -o /tmp/digicert-ca.pem \
  https://cacerts.digicert.com/DigiCertGlobalG2TLSRSASHA2562020CA1-1.crt.pem

# Download DigiCert root CA
curl -o /tmp/digicert-root.pem \
  https://cacerts.digicert.com/DigiCertGlobalRootG2.crt.pem

# Get full cert chain from server
openssl s_client -connect gitlab.ttmtech.com:443 -showcerts </dev/null 2>/dev/null | \
  sed -n '/-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----/,/-----END CERTIFICATE-----/p' > /tmp/gitlab-fullchain.pem

# Combine into one file
cat /tmp/gitlab-fullchain.pem /tmp/digicert-ca.pem /tmp/digicert-root.pem > /tmp/gitlab-combined.pem

# Create Kubernetes secret
kubectl create namespace gitlab-runner

kubectl create secret generic gitlab-ttmtech-ca \
  -n gitlab-runner \
  --from-file=gitlab.ttmtech.com.crt=/tmp/gitlab-combined.pem
```

Verify the cert works from inside the runner pod:

```bash
kubectl exec -it <runner-pod> -n gitlab-runner -- bash
openssl s_client -connect gitlab.ttmtech.com:443 \
  -CAfile /home/gitlab-runner/.gitlab-runner/certs/gitlab.ttmtech.com.crt
# Should show: Verify return code: 0 (ok)
```

